You have your syntax reversed, it would be Node <i></i>prev_link, and cur_entry would be a Node* not a Node.  Also your loop condition goes in the middle and the per-stage operation goes last.<p>I still don't get what you are doing here, since previous never updated, it always points to the list_head. So you would be changing the first node to point to the node after the one you are removing, which means you remove all nodes after the first up through the to-be removed node since the head is now pointing to the next.<p>Here's my stabs at it:<p><pre><code>    node **prevNode, *nextNode;
    // Doesn't work, curr becomes null and can't reference next
    for(prevNode = &list_head, currNode = *prevNode; 
        currNode != NULL; 
        currNode = *prevNode, prevNode = &currNode->next)
        if(must_remove(**currNode) {
            **prevNode = currNode->next;
            *prevNode = NULL;
        }
</code></pre>
The only other way I could think to remove a singly linked list element is the dumb way:<p><pre><code>    node *curr = list_head, *prev = NULL;
    for(; curr != NULL; prev = curr, curr = curr->next) {
        if(must_remove(*curr) {
            if(prev == NULL)
                list_head = curr->next;
            prev->next == curr->next;
            curr = NULL;
        }
    }</code></pre>
